Heres how to do it step-by-step in your existing code:

Step-by-step: Adding Background Music

    (() => {

  3. Now start the music when the game begins.

    js

    Right before resetLevel(true);, add:

    js
    music.play().catch(() => {

  4. (Optional) If you want to restart the music when going to Level 1,

Ah! That makes sense now. The reason you still dont hear the music is because of how modern browsers block autoplay of audio files. Even though your code calls music.play(), browsers like Chrome, Edge, and Firefox will not play any audio without a direct user interaction (click, keypress, etc.). This is not a code bugits a browser security restriction.

Heres the fix: we need to start the music only after a user clicks anywhere or presses a key. Lets modify your code so that the first user interaction starts the music reliably. Copy this part at the start of your script, before music.play():

javascript
//  Background music
const music = new Audio("soda-pop.mp3");
music.loop = true;
music.volume = 0.5;

// Start music only after first user interaction
function startMusic() {
  music.play().catch(() => console.log("Waiting for user interaction to start music."));
  window.removeEventListener('click', startMusic);
  window.removeEventListener('keydown', startMusic);
}
window.addEventListener('click', startMusic);
window.addEventListener('keydown', startMusic);

Then remove all other music.play() calls.

How this works:

  • The browser waits until any click or keypress happens.

  • As soon as that happens, the music starts.

  • After that, it loops automatically.

Ah! Thats simple. You just need a direct URL to an audio file that the browser can access. Heres how to swap it:

  1. Find a song in .mp3 (or .ogg) format thats hosted online.

    • Some good free sources:

      • Mixkit

      • FreeSound

      • Pixabay Music

  2. Copy the direct link to the file. It must end with .mp3 or .ogg.

    • Example:

      text
      https://assets.mixkit.co/active_storage/sfx/2869/2869-preview.mp3

  3. Replace the URL in your code where you create the Audio object:

javascript
// Original
const music = new Audio("https://assets.mixkit.co/active_storage/sfx/2869/2869-preview.mp3");

// New song
const music = new Audio("PASTE_YOUR_NEW_SONG_URL_HERE");
music.loop = true;
music.volume = 0.5;

  1. Save and reload your page. The new song will play when you start the game.

Important: The file must be hosted online; local files (like "soda-pop.mp3") usually wont work in a browser unless you run a server or use a tool like StackBlitz with the file uploaded.

Perfect! I can guide you step by step. On FreeSound, most sounds are downloadable but not all links are direct URLs to the filethe browser can only play a file if its a direct link ending in .mp3 or .ogg. Heres how to get it properly:

Step 1: Download the sound

  1. Click Download on the FreeSound page for your chosen sound.

  2. Save it to your computer.

Step 2: Host the file online

You cannot use a local file path in your browser for this kind of game. You need an online URL. You have a few free options:

  1. GitHub

    • Upload the .mp3 to a GitHub repository.

    • Go to the file in your repo, click Raw, and copy the URL.

    • Example URL:

      arduino
      https://raw.githubusercontent.com/username/repo/main/song.mp3

  2. Free hosting services like:

    • file.io

    • AnonFiles

    • Vocaroo for short audio clips

  3. Dropbox / Google Drive (with a public link)

    • For Google Drive, you need to tweak the link to make it direct-download.

    • Example:

      bash
      https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=FILE_ID

Step 3: Update your code

Once you have the direct URL, replace it here:

javascript
const music = new Audio("PASTE_YOUR_NEW_SONG_URL_HERE");
music.loop = true;
music.volume = 0.5;
